Grocery Store Marketing Analysis

Author

Pete Woo

This dataset comes from a ficticious grocery store by an owner names Gerry. Gerry is investigating a potential promotion and also wants to identify ways to improve his sales/marketing strategy. They offer a membership that results in 20% off all items for a monthly fee of $999. However, they are offering a discounted membership price of $499. They want insight on their customer behavioral data and to find out which customers are the best options to target for this promotion.



This project will consist of Exploratory Data Analysis, Inferential Analysis, Customer Segmentation, and lastly Predictive Analysis.

Imputing Missing Values of Income

Code 
# Loop through indices of rows where "Income" is NaN
for index in na_income_indices:

    current_row = df.loc[index]

    mean_income = round(df[(df["Education"] == current_row["Education"]) & (df["Age"] >= current_row["Age"] - 3) & (df["Age"] <= current_row["Age"] + 3)]["Income"].mean(), 1)

    df.loc[index, "Income"] = mean_income

My methodology for imputing missing values of Income was to impute the average income of other instances with similar Education level and Age.

The 2 Criteria for Education Level and Age:

  1. Identical Education Level (PhD, Masters, 2n Cycle, Graduation, or Basic)
  2. Age within 3 years of person with missing income’s Age
When taking the average income of people with Identical Education Level and Age (PhD, 67), there were too few instances. I felt that adding a plus/minus 3 year age tolerance would increase the number of people the average income was taken from without sacrificing too much demographic difference.

spending_df = spending_df.reset_index(drop = True)

Code 
from plotnine import ggplot, aes, geom_bar, geom_line, geom_point, scale_y_continuous, labs, theme, element_text, geom_hline, annotate

spending_df["Cumulative"] = spending_df["Mean"].cumsum()
spending_df["Percentage"] = spending_df["Cumulative"] / spending_df["Mean"].sum() * 100

spending_df['Variable'] = pd.Categorical(spending_df['Variable'], 
                                           categories=spending_df['Variable'], 
                                           ordered=True)

(ggplot(spending_df, aes(x='Variable', y='Mean')) +
    geom_bar(stat='identity', fill='steelblue') +
    geom_line(aes(y='Cumulative', group=1), color='red', size=1) +
    geom_hline(yintercept=484.84, linetype='dashed', color='black', size=1) +
    annotate("text", x=1.1, y=500, label="80% Target Line", color="black", ha="center") +
    geom_point(aes(y='Cumulative'), color='red', size=3) +

    labs(title='Pareto Chart',
         x='Category',
         y='Mean Revenue per Customer') +
    theme(axis_text_x=element_text(rotation=45, hjust=1))
)
From this pareto chart, we can see that Wine and Meat make up about 80% of Gerry’s Grocery Store’s total revenue while only accounting for 33% of the product selection. Therefore, Wine and Meat should be the main priority and customers with high spending tendencies for those 2 categories are the most valuable. Gerry’s Grocery Store reflects the 80/20 rule in business.

from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error, r2_score

df = df.dropna()

df_with_dummies = pd.get_dummies(df, columns=["Education", "Marital_Status"], drop_first=True)
dummy_cols = df_with_dummies.columns[df_with_dummies.columns.str.startswith(('Education_', 'Marital_Status_'))]
df_with_dummies[dummy_cols] = df_with_dummies[dummy_cols].astype(int)

From the Linear Regression of Wine Spending. We can see which factors increase or decrease wine spending. There is a notable difference between parents with younger children vs. teenage children. The younger a parent’s children are, the less they are spending on wine. This makes sense because younger children require more supervision and parents do not have as much time to lounge around and enjoy a glass of wine. It is key for Gus to avoid targeting parents with young children in order to maximize promotion gains.

import statsmodels.formula.api as smf

df["cAge"] = df["Age"] - df["Age"].mean()
df["low_age"] = df["cAge"] + df["Age"].std()

df["cNumCatalogPurchases"] = df["NumCatalogPurchases"] - df["NumCatalogPurchases"].mean()

spotlight = smf.ols('MntMeatProducts ~ low_age * cNumCatalogPurchases', data = df).fit()
print(spotlight.summary())

Principal Component Analysis

Code 
from sklearn.decomposition import PCA
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler


# Step 1: Standardize the data
scaler = StandardScaler()
scaled_data = scaler.fit_transform(df_with_dummies)

# Step 2: Apply PCA
pca = PCA(n_components=2)  # Choose how many principal components you want
pca_result = pca.fit_transform(scaled_data)

# Step 3: Explained variance ratio
explained_variance = pca.explained_variance_ratio_

# Print the explained variance for each principal component
print(f"Explained Variance Ratio: {explained_variance}")

# Step 4: Visualize the first two principal components
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
plt.scatter(pca_result[:, 0], pca_result[:, 1], c='b', edgecolor='k')
plt.title('PCA - First Two Principal Components')
plt.xlabel('Principal Component 1')
plt.ylabel('Principal Component 2')
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

# Optional: If you want to see the cumulative explained variance to decide how many components to keep:
cumulative_variance = np.cumsum(pca.explained_variance_ratio_)

plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))
plt.plot(range(1, len(cumulative_variance) + 1), cumulative_variance, marker='o', linestyle='--', color='b')
plt.title('Cumulative Explained Variance by Number of Principal Components')
plt.xlabel('Number of Principal Components')
plt.ylabel('Cumulative Explained Variance')
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()
